The Medium Is the Message

Early in my career, as a twentysomething editor at The New York Times, the =
workday often ended late, some time after 8 p.m., and was often followed by=
 a brief trip down the elevator and through the lobby to the back entrance =
of Wolfgang=E2=80=99s=E2=80=94the steakhouse that occupied a retail space i=
n the Times Building at 620 Eighth Ave. I was a part of a tight-knit group =
of journalists and editors and digital novices who loved what we did, and o=
ften needed an hour or so to chew it over before heading to the subway. We=
=E2=80=99d devour those decadent homemade potato chips=E2=80=94their pungen=
t smell permeated the whole joint=E2=80=94while drinking Manhattans and phi=
losophizing about where the industry was heading.

This was around the time, of course, when what used to be called print medi=
a was experiencing the first pangs of existential dread=E2=80=94the ones
that had been endured years earlier by the music industry and would eventua=
lly ripple through linear television and Hollywood. I=E2=80=99d grown up in=
 the magazine industry, once a thriving concern that, it was becoming clear=
, consumers simply didn=E2=80=99t covet any longer. The long lead times and=
 expensive fixed costs, among other issues, were prohibitive in an era when=
 readers had myriad other options.

Some limitations were secular, others stemmed from culture and a failure of=
 imagination. At the Times Magazine, during those fraught years of the Grea=
t Recession, editors had to select feature stories and covers weeks and mon=
ths before they hit the Sunday paper bundle and internet. How in the world =
could we predict topics that would be relevant in the future? Our best gues=
swork could be upended by a last-minute newsbreak or unforeseen event. It w=
as just another headache in an industry filled with them.

What=E2=80=99s more: Magazines had been bound by the
notion that they needed to continually mix up their coverage areas to serve=
 as narrow and broad an audience as possible. If you put, say, Hillary Clin=
ton on the cover of the magazine one week, you probably couldn=E2=80=99t do=
 that again=E2=80=94according to this perverse logic=E2=80=94for a couple y=
ears. If you ran a professional athlete on the cover, you wouldn=E2=80=99t =
put another jock on for months. If you even pitched such a notion in an ide=
as meeting, some grizzled older colleague would surely say, =E2=80=9CWe jus=
t did that,=E2=80=9D and the room would hum with agreement.

As a result, editors settled on a production line of evergreen stories that=
 were manufactured to be broadly appealing but were almost parodic. One tha=
t I recall from that era was about what whales might be telling us humans. =
(In typical Times hide-covering, we couldn=E2=80=99t definitively declare i=
f they were sending us these subaquatic signals or not.) Anyway, a lot of e=
xogenous factors killed
the magazine business, but a lack of creativity certainly contributed.

Amid all this, the best piece of editorial advice I ever received came from=
 one of those work postmortems at Wolfgang=E2=80=99s. I was talking with Hu=
go Lindgren, then the editor-in-chief of the Times Magazine and one of the =
great practitioners of the art form, about a whole host of work items, imag=
ining the future of the business, and wondering about my place in it. Then =
Hugo made a side comment that I=E2=80=99ll never forget. Magazines were abo=
ut connection, he reminded me=E2=80=94bringing an audience into a world the=
y could never access otherwise. The medium was going to change, obviously, =
but the underlying message never would.

The Leitmotifs

Even as I comb my own gray hairs, I often think of that line, which defines=
 so much of the work here at Puck. As you well know, Puck has its leitmotif=
s and obsessions=E2=80=94and we fully embrace them. These are our way of co=
nnecting with our audience and allowing them to access otherwise inaccessib=
le terrain.

A number of those fixations were on display this week. Just at the moment w=
hen it seemed that Shari Redstone was finally ready to part ways with Param=
ount Global, her family heirloom, she appears to be getting a little jitter=
y. In Shari=E2=80=99s
Moment of Hard Truth ( https://puck.news/shari-redstone-wavers-on-skydance-=
bid-for-paramount/?utm_campaign=3DThe+Backstory+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%286%2F8%2F24=
%29&utm_content=3DThe+Backstory+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%286%2F8%2F24%29&utm_medium=
=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ), M=
att Belloni reveals some of Redstone=E2=80=99s last-minute wavering. And in=
 The Shari Soap Opera=E2=80=99s Final Twist ( https://puck.news/shari-redst=
one-final-ask/?utm_campaign=3DThe+Backstory+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%286%2F8%2F24%29&=
utm_content=3DThe+Backstory+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%286%2F8%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Dema=
il_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ), Bill Co=
han breaks the news of a last-minute retrade that might impede the transact=
ion. After all, so many deals die with age.

Meanwhile, as the biggest media C.E.O.s compete for a slice of Adam Silver=
=E2=80=99s $76 billion pie, John Ourand articulated one underappreciated el=
ement of the deal: So much of the pay TV and streaming economy hinges on th=
ese game packages because there won=E2=80=99t be any other major rights on =
the block for years. In his excellent piece, Is There Life After the NBA? (=
 https://puck.news/is-there-life-after-the-nba/?utm_campaign=3DThe+Backstor=
y+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%286%2F8%2F24%29&utm_content=3DThe+Backstory+-+SUBSCRIBERS+=
%286%2F8%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_ter=
m=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ), John brilliantly answered his own rhetorical ques=
tion. There is vitality for some, but not for others.

And, lastly, so much of the week=E2=80=99s work coalesced around the consta=
nt executive shuffling and deal flow that are endemic to an economy complet=
ing a digital transformation. In Est=C3=A9e=E2=80=99s $3.6 Billion Revitali=
zing Cream ( https://puck.news/estee-lauder-3-6-billion-revitalizing-cream/=
?utm_campaign=3DThe+Backstory+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%286%2F8%2F24%29&utm_content=3D=
The+Backstory+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%286%2F8%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_=
source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ), Rachel Strugatz chron=
icled the latest chapter in a historic business=E2=80=99s attempt to catch =
up with the times. Similarly, Lauren Sherman=E2=80=99s breathtaking Heaven =
and Chanel ( https://puck.news/who-should-succeed-virginie-viard-at-chanel/=
?utm_campaign=3DThe+Backstory+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%286%2F8%2F24%29&utm_content=3D=
The+Backstory+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%286%2F8%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_=
source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) dissects the dawn of a=
 new era at the post-Lagerfeld, and now post-Virginie Viard,
maison as it redefines its identity.

But if you only have time to read one piece this weekend, I=E2=80=99d turn =
your attention to Dylan Byers=E2=80=99 excellent =E2=80=98Post=E2=80=99 Mor=
tem ( https://puck.news/the-real-story-behind-sally-buzbee-departure-from-w=
ashington-post/?utm_campaign=3DThe+Backstory+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%286%2F8%2F24%29=
&utm_content=3DThe+Backstory+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%286%2F8%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Dem=
ail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ). The Po=
st, like the Times I knew nearly 15 years ago, is trapped in a moment of ex=
istential
ennui=E2=80=94longing for a previous era, able to comprehend that it needs =
to pivot, but reluctant to take the leap. It=E2=80=99s a story about people=
 and corporations as old as time. And in many ways, it is the story of our =
age, and precisely what you should expect from Puck.

Have a great weekend,
Jon

